  "text": "Since the third bracket gives structure functions, this is far more complicated than a Lie algebra (it is a Lie algebroid [CITATION_1] ). (8) is the closure of the Lie algebra of 3-diffeomorphisms on the 3-surface, whilst (9) just means that H is a scalar density; neither of these have any dynamical content. It is the third bracket then that has dynamical content. The Dirac algebroid has remarkable properties at the classical level, as exposited in Sec 5. However, that the Dirac algebroid of the classical GR constraints is not a Lie algebra does limit many a quantization approach [17] . The Diff(M) that are not among the Diff(Σ) do cause a number of serious difficulties with quantization schemes [17] . The quantum GR Hamiltonian constraint is a Wheeler-DeWitt equation (WDE),",
